ys its for locational use only (eg. doko ni, Dore ni, etc.) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uchronothestampede.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Chrono The Stampede</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(1/24/02 4:44:53 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=615.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.shuster.org/matt/cticons/cronow.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: 'NI' usage</span><hr size=1> all i can say is i've only seen it used in directional uses, meaning the usual in/on...whatever. but i could defenitely be wrong <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=superflat>superflat</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(1/24/02 9:38:04 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=615.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: 'NI' usage</span><hr size=1> Ni has a LOT of usages outside of directional/locational.  In the case of hontou ni, its adverbial.  Hontou means truth, hontou ni means truthfuly.  When you wish to change a noun or na-adjetive to an adverb, you add a ni to the end (e.g. gutaiteki become gutaiteki ni).  In the case of i-adjectives you replace the i with ku (e.g. hayai become hayaku).<br>
<br>
Another possible usage is sort of as a &quot;targetting particle&quot; (that's not the technical term, its just the way I think of it).  Like for example: sensei ni kikimashita (I asked the teacher).  This is also used a lot when constructing passive sentences, but you probably don't need to worry about that right now.  A few simpler usages are temporal (as in: nanji ni au tsumori ka), expressing purpose (as in: eiga wo mi ni ikimashita), 'per' (as in:  ishuukan ni san kai), and finally kind of as a criterion (like: watashi ni ha dekinai).<br>
<br>
